body: @hariharans29 Is there any update for this ticket? Thanks.
Hi @lihan - Thanks for checking in. I haven't had the chance to investigate this. Is this a blocking issue or are you able to use a different activation layer to unblock yourself ?
And does this repro with 1.9.0 as well ?
Hi @hariharans29 The issue remain in 1.9.0. For my use case, the ONNX deployment will be pending on this issue. Currently running on original Pytorch model.

Hi @lihan : Can you please just paste your model.onnx file here ? For some reason, I have some issues while trying to export your Torch model from the provided source code. 

Since the ONNX standard doesn't have an RRelu activation operator, I would like to see how that gets exported as into ONNX from Torch. If it is an ORT issue, we will try to provide a fix in the next release.

I figured out the reason for the nondeterministic results. Unfortunately, I don't think it is due to a bug in ORT and hence can't be fixed.

This is RRelu's spec: https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/generated/torch.nn.RReLU.html. I think `a` is sampled once and fixed once this operator is instantiated (i.e.) this operator is deterministic.

Since, RRelu is not part of the ONNX standard opset, the operator gets "composed" in ONNX like this:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/138949693-9151135d-98e3-4cc0-b63f-4c6098f1cbc5.png)

`RandomUniformLike` picks a different `a` for every Run. As you can imagine, the presence of a random generation function `RandomUniformLike` is not going to make results deterministic. 

So, the core problem is: `a` is fixed for the RRelu op in PyTorch vs `a` is not fixed in ONNX. Can you please open an issue in PyTorch and clarify if this export is correct ?

Tagging @BowenBao / @garymm for their thoughts.

This appears to match the PyTorch behavior, so I don't think it's a bug:

```python
import torch

m = torch.nn.RReLU(0.1, 0.3)
input = torch.tensor([0.5, -0.5])
for _ in range(3):
  print(m(input))
```

Prints:
```
tensor([ 0.5000, -0.1394])
tensor([ 0.5000, -0.0921])
tensor([ 0.5000, -0.0792])
```

Notice it produces different results each time it runs on the same input.

Thanks @garymm. So,  it looks like `a` is sampled on every Run in PyTorch as well.

@lihan - ORT's behavior seems to be expected. Not sure how you got deterministic results on every run unless the value of `a` sampled every time was the exact same value.
Closing as this seems like the expected behavior. Please re-open if you have any concerns.
